\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 1. INTRODUCTION\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 1.1 Context and Motivation\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 Safety-Critical Systems (SCSs) are systems in which failures or malfunctions can lead to severe consequences, including loss of life, significant property damage, or environmental harm. The increasing reliance on software to control these systems has amplified their complexity, making safety assurance a paramount concern throughout the development lifecycle.\
Evidence suggests that most safety-related failures originate in the early phases of development, particularly during Requirements Engineering (RE). Errors, omissions, or ambiguities in safety requirements can propagate through design and implementation, leading to latent failures that are costly and difficult to correct in later stages. This highlights the need for methodologies that integrate safety analysis directly into the RE process.\
Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering has emerged as an effective paradigm for modeling requirements in early stages, focusing on the "why" behind system functionalities. Languages like iStar 2.0 provide a social modeling framework suited for understanding the logic of complex systems. To specifically address safety concerns, the iStar4Safety extension was developed, introducing constructs such as Safety Goals, Hazards, and Safety Tasks.\
Concurrently, in the domain of Safety Engineering (SE), modern techniques like System-Theoretic Process Analysis (STPA) have gained prominence. Unlike traditional methods focused on component failures, STPA analyzes safety as an emergent system property, identifying Unsafe Control Actions (UCAs) and flawed interactions between components.\
Despite the availability of advanced techniques in both disciplines, a significant gap persists. The RESafety process was proposed to systematically integrate the intentional modeling of iStar4Safety with the analytical rigor of STPA through a seven-step iterative workflow. However, the manual application of the RESafety process presents severe challenges:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b High Cognitive Load:
\f1\b0  Requires analysts to be proficient in two distinct and complex methodologies (iStar and STPA) and to manually map concepts between them.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Time-Consuming and Error-Prone:
\f1\b0  The process involves creating and updating numerous artifacts (diagrams, tables, lists). Manually ensuring consistency and traceability across these artifacts is tedious and susceptible to human error.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b High Adoption Barrier:
\f1\b0  The inherent complexity and effort required for manual application create a significant barrier for teams and organizations, limiting practical adoption.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The motivation for this dissertation arises from the need to overcome these challenges. The successful development of tools like SafeSecRETS has demonstrated the feasibility and value of computational support. Furthermore, recent advances in Artificial Intelligence, particularly Large Language Models (LLMs), offer an innovative opportunity to automate analytical and generative tasks. This research proposes the design and development of RESafety Tool, a software tool based on modern web technologies (Angular and Quarkus) that not only implements the process in a user-friendly manner but also integrates an AI assistant to automate essential steps.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1.2 Problem Definition\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Despite the availability of advanced techniques in both Requirements Engineering (RE) and Safety Engineering (SE), a significant methodological and practical gap persists between the two disciplines. Requirements engineers often lack the specialized knowledge needed to conduct rigorous safety analyses, while safety engineers may struggle to translate their findings back into traceable, well-formed requirement models. This methodological disconnect hinders communication among teams and frequently results in inconsistencies between the specified objectives for the system and its safety constraints.\
{\listtext	\'95	}To mitigate this problem, the RESafety process was proposed as a systematic methodology to integrate the intentional modeling of iStar4Safety with the analytical rigor of STPA. RESafety provides a seven-step iterative workflow that guides analysts from high-level scope definition to the detailed specification of safety requirements derived from hazard analysis.\
{\listtext	\'95	}However, the core problem addressed in this research is that the strictly manual application of the RESafety process presents severe challenges that impede its large-scale adoption in the industry. The main obstacles include:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b High Cognitive Load:
\f1\b0  Manual execution requires analysts to be highly proficient in two distinct and complex methodologies (iStar and STPA), necessitating continuous mapping and translation of concepts between them.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Time-Consuming and Error-Prone Process:
\f1\b0  The manual workflow involves creating and updating numerous artifacts, including diagrams, matrices, and lists. Ensuring consistency and traceability among these artifacts manually is a tedious task susceptible to human error.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b High Adoption Barrier:
\f1\b0  The inherent complexity and the considerable effort required for manual application create a significant barrier for teams and organizations, limiting the practical adoption of this approach.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Therefore, the research problem focuses on the difficulty of applying the RESafety process efficiently and consistently, highlighting the need for tool support to overcome these operational obstacles and improve the effectiveness of safety requirements engineering.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1.3 Research Objectives\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}To guide the conduct of this work and solve the problem detailed in the previous section, this dissertation is driven by the following research questions:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b RQ1:
\f1\b0  How can a modern web technology stack (Angular frontend with Quarkus backend integration) be used to create a collaborative web tool that effectively implements the seven-step RESafety process while preserving traceability between iStar4Safety and STPA artifacts?\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b RQ2:
\f1\b0  How can Generative Artificial Intelligence be integrated into the RESafety workflow, within this architecture, to assist the generation and refinement of safety artifacts without removing analyst control over the final results?\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b RQ3:
\f1\b0  To what extent does a tool-supported, AI-enhanced implementation of RESafety improve perceived usefulness and ease of use for analysts compared to a purely manual process?\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb255\sa255\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1.3.1 General Objective\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\sa255\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The general objective of this research is to design and develop RESafety Tool, a web-based tool using Angular and integrated Quarkus services, to provide a guided, step-by-step implementation of the RESafety process with practical support for traceability and artifact management.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa255\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1.3.2 Specific Objectives\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	Architect and integrate an Artificial Intelligence Assistant within the tool, capable of suggesting and structuring safety artifacts from analyst-provided context through backend APIs while preserving human validation before acceptance.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	Demonstrate the applicability of the tool by applying it to a well-defined case study of a Safety-Critical System.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	Conduct a preliminary evaluation of the tool based on established frameworks, such as the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM), to assess its potential for practical adoption.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1.4 Justification and Contributions\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The increasing complexity of Safety-Critical Systems requires methods that ensure their integrity starting from the requirements phase. Although the RESafety process offers a solid methodological foundation by uniting Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering (iStar4Safety) and Safety Engineering (STPA), the adoption of this integration in practice is severely limited by technical complexity and the high effort involved in manual execution. The creation of an automated tool is justified by the pressing need to reduce the cognitive load on engineers and decrease the susceptibility to human errors associated with managing such dense artifacts.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The dissertation addresses the significant challenge of practically applying complex, integrated safety analysis methodologies. The manual effort required constitutes a barrier to adoption, as it demands acute expertise in two professional fronts (Requirements and Safety). Therefore, the main contribution of this work is the conception and development of the RESafety Tool platform, which operationalizes and optimizes the RESafety workflow through contemporary web technologies.\
{\listtext	\'95	}By structuring the tool through an Angular interface integrated with Quarkus APIs, an embedded iStar4Safety modeller, and an intelligent assistant, this dissertation consolidates the following academic and technological contributions:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Tool-Supported Workflow for RESafety:
\f1\b0  RESafety Tool delivers the first tool-based implementation of the RESafety process, materializing what was previously only a theoretical methodology into a systematic, practical workflow. Its collaborative dynamic via a web platform democratizes access and collaboration for geographically distributed teams.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Artificial Intelligence Integration for Automation in Safety Analysis:
\f1\b0  This research pioneers the use of Large Language Models (LLMs) to assist knowledge generation in critical RESafety activities. In the implemented application, the assistant already supports scope-definition activities with structured prompts, JSON-oriented responses, and merge-and-review behavior, establishing a concrete basis for extending AI support to later analytical stages without bypassing engineering judgment.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Demonstration of Modern Web Technologies Suitability for Domain-Specific Engineering:
\f1\b0  The study validates the technical efficacy of combining Angular and Quarkus for domain-specific engineering software. The resulting application demonstrates that authenticated navigation, reactive forms, embedded modelling tools, and REST-based service integration can be combined into a maintainable environment suited to the disciplined management of safety artifacts.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1.5 Structure of the Dissertation\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}This document is organized and structured as follows:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Chapter 2 - Theoretical Foundation and Literature Review:
\f1\b0  Presents the theoretical framework covering Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering, the iStar 2.0 and iStar4Safety modeling languages, the System-Theoretic Process Analysis (STPA) technique, and a detailed review of the RESafety integration process.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Chapter 3 - Research Methodology:
\f1\b0  Describes the adoption of the Design Science Research (DSR) methodology, which acts as the guiding framework for the conception, development, and formal evaluation activities of the RESafety Tool tool.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Chapter 4 - Conception and Architecture of the RESafety Tool Tool:
\f1\b0  Presents the technical details and design decisions of the RESafety Tool tool, including its Angular frontend, Quarkus service integration, user workflows, current implementation boundaries, and the technological implementation of the integrated Artificial Intelligence assistant.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Chapter 5 - Artifact Demonstration and Validation:
\f1\b0  In conjunction with DSR guidelines, this chapter demonstrates the practical application of the built tool using a case study from the literature and details the preliminary evaluation strategy with experts aimed at assessing acceptance.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Chapter 6 - Final Considerations:
\f1\b0  Synthesizes the general conclusions and contributions of this research. Additionally, it provides detailed answers to the proposed research questions, discusses the limitations of the current study, and offers objective directions for future work and improvements.\
