\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2. THEORETICAL FOUNDATION AND LITERATURE REVIEW\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}This chapter establishes the theoretical foundations necessary for understanding the context and contributions achieved by this research. It covers the essential methodologies that the RESafety Tool tool integrates: the Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering paradigm, the iStar4Safety modeling language, and the STPA safety analysis technique, which form the pillars of the RESafety process. Additionally, the technological bases of Artificial Intelligence applied to the automation of these practices are introduced.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2.1 Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Traditional Requirements Engineering (RE) typically focuses on defining exactly what the system should do, often specifying behaviors and functions disconnected from the stakeholders' initial intentions. In contrast, Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering presents itself as a refined RE paradigm, focusing primarily on modeling the high-level goals, objectives, and intentions of the interested parties. Its main purpose is to traceably guide the elicitation and specification of system requirements starting from primary desires and organizational motivations.\
{\listtext	\'95	}Thus, models built with the Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering paradigm direct their emphasis to the fundamental axis of "why," that is, the underlying reasons dictating that certain software characteristics or operational processes must exist in the sociotechnical system. By adopting the intentional focus of "why," Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering provides a robust rationale, ensuring a continuous traceability matrix that starts from high-level corporate and strategic objectives, progressively descending in hierarchical layers until reaching the most specific operational requirements.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The traceability generated by this mapping is crucial during the safety analysis and system evolution stages. If a critical goal is not met, the analyst has the visual and analytical means to traverse the models inversely, identify the failure agents associated with mitigation tasks, and act on the specification or reengineering of the proposed functionalities. This foundational understanding justifies and paves the way for the use of modeling extensions to handle specific scenarios where "safe goals" need to be effectively translated into constrained behaviors in the software.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2.2 Modeling Languages: iStar 2.0 and iStar4Safety\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The iStar language is a prominent intentional modeling framework used to model the strategic relationships between actors within a sociotechnical system. To perform this mapping, iStar 2.0 uses two main types of conceptual models:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Strategic Dependency (SD) Model:
\f1\b0  Describes the network of dependencies between actors, illustrating who depends on whom for goals to be achieved, tasks to be performed, resources to be furnished, or qualities to be met.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Strategic Rationale (SR) Model:
\f1\b0  Provides a deeper view by looking "inside" actors to demonstrate their internal reasoning. It details how actors' goals are refined into tasks and how they depend on additional resources and qualities to achieve their purposes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Although the iStar 2.0 language offers great robustness for general strategic modeling, it lacks specific constructs to explicitly represent safety-related concepts. In order to bridge this gap, the iStar4Safety extension was proposed. This extension introduces new stereotyped elements and relationships to the base language with the primary purpose of modeling a Preliminary Safety Analysis, such as:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b <<SafetyGoal>>:
\f1\b0  Represents an objective that is critical for system safety. The failure or non-fulfillment of a SafetyGoal can directly lead to an accident.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b <<Hazard>>:
\f1\b0  Defines a system state that, under certain conditions, can lead to an accident. In iStar4Safety notation, a Hazard is visually modeled as an anti-goal that obstructs the achievement of a SafetyGoal.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b <<SafetyTask>>:
\f1\b0  A task formulated specifically for the purpose of mitigating or preventing the manifestation of an established hazard.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b <<Safety Resource>>:
\f1\b0  An element that denotes a critical and indispensable resource for the execution of a SafetyTask or for the fulfillment of a SafetyGoal.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Obstructs Link:
\f1\b0  This is a modeling relationship indicating that the occurrence of a certain Hazard can prevent a SafetyGoal from being achieved.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2.3 Safety Engineering and the STPA Technique\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Unlike Requirements Engineering, which focuses on defining desired behavior, Safety Engineering is dedicated to ensuring that a system does not cause unacceptable harm to the environment or people. In the context of modern cyber-physical systems, where software assumes control of critical functions, the traditional approach focused exclusively on component reliability (such as FMEA - Failure Mode and Effects Analysis) becomes insufficient. System complexity, with unexpected interactions between software, hardware, and human intervention, demands methods that treat safety as an emergent property.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The STPA (System-Theoretic Process Analysis) technique is based on systems theory and the control view (STAMP model - System-Theoretic Accident Model and Processes). Instead of decomposing the system in search of hardware failures, STPA models the system as a hierarchical control structure, where safety is defined by the effectiveness of the control mechanisms imposed on the components. A system is considered safe if safety constraints are enforced and maintained at all levels of this structure.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The analytical process of STPA identifies how the lack of enforcement of safety constraints or the execution of inadequate control actions can lead to loss states (Losses). The focus is on identifying:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Unsafe Control Actions (UCAs):
\f1\b0  Control actions that, in a specific context, lead to a safety loss.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Loss Scenarios:
\f1\b0  The causal trajectories that explain why a UCA might occur, considering sensor failures, actuator failures, operational errors, or unexpected software interactions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The integration of iStar4Safety with STPA, consolidated in the RESafety process, allows the safety goals identified in Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering to be refined and validated through the analytical rigor of STPA. This ensures that the derived safety requirements are not just "high-level wishes," but technically grounded constraints that effectively control system behavior to prevent loss scenarios.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2.4 The RESafety Integration Process\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The RESafety process was developed to bridge the gap between high-level requirements analysis and technical hazard analysis, proposing a systematic integration that leverages the strengths of both domains. The essence of RESafety lies in an iterative workflow structured in seven main steps, which connect intentional goal modeling with systemic control analysis:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}1.	
\f0\b Step 1: Definition of System Scope and Objectives:
\f1\b0  Begins with modeling the system using iStar4Safety, focusing on identifying actors, strategic goals, and basic functional requirements.\
{\listtext	2.	}2.	
\f0\b Step 2: Identification of Hazards and Safety Goals:
\f1\b0  Initial analysis of operational risks to elicit SafetyGoals and Hazards associated with the operating environment.\
{\listtext	3.	}3.	
\f0\b Step 3: Risk Modeling in iStar4Safety:
\f1\b0  Integration of the identified hazards into the iStar model, using the Obstructs Link construct to demonstrate how these risks threaten SafetyGoals and strategic objectives.\
{\listtext	4.	}4.	
\f0\b Step 4: Translation to the STPA Control Structure:
\f1\b0  Conversion of iStar model components (actors and dependencies) into the hierarchical control structure required by STPA, identifying controllers and controlled processes.\
{\listtext	5.	}5.	
\f0\b Step 5: Identification of UCAs (Unsafe Control Actions):
\f1\b0  Systematic analysis of control actions within the structure identified in Step 4 to find instances where the execution of control, or its absence, generates hazardous scenarios.\
{\listtext	6.	}6.	
\f0\b Step 6: Derivation of Loss Scenarios and Constraints:
\f1\b0  Exploration of the underlying causes of UCAs (Loss Scenarios) and formulation of safety constraints that must be imposed to eliminate or mitigate such failures.\
{\listtext	7.	}7.	
\f0\b Step 7: Requirement Refinement and Traceability:
\f1\b0  Finalization of the process by translating safety constraints into traceable system requirements, which are mapped back to the original iStar4Safety diagrams, ensuring that the proposed solution meets safety needs without compromising strategic objectives.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	8.	}This systematic flow is the core of what RESafety Tool seeks to automate, providing the necessary interface for the engineer to navigate between the strategic vision of iStar diagrams and the technical vision of STPA tables and safety scenarios.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	10.	}2.5 Artificial Intelligence and Prompt Engineering in Requirements Generation\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	11.	}The advent of Large Language Models (LLMs) has introduced unprecedented capabilities in natural language understanding and generation, significantly impacting software engineering practices. In the context of Requirements Engineering (RE), LLMs offer the potential to automate tedious analytical tasks, such as eliciting requirements, checking for inconsistencies, and transforming high-level goals into technical specifications.\
{\listtext	12.	}However, applying Generative AI to Safety-Critical Systems requires strict adherence to domain rigor, as hallucinations or imprecise generations can lead to catastrophic oversights. This is where Prompt Engineering becomes essential. Prompt Engineering is the systematic process of designing, refining, and optimizing the input text (prompts) provided to an LLM to guide its output toward desired, highly specific formats and conceptual constraints.\
{\listtext	13.	}In the architecture of the RESafety Tool tool, Prompt Engineering serves as the vital technical bridge between the Java (Quarkus) backend and the external LLM APIs. Instead of allowing open-ended interactions, the tool employs rigorous, programmatic prompt templates. These templates automatically inject specific domain context\'97such as the exact phrasing of an Unsafe Control Action (UCA) or the detailed causal factors of a Loss Scenario\'97into a set of precise, pre-validated instructions.\
{\listtext	14.	}For example, when deriving a Controller Constraint from a UCA, the prompt template instructs the LLM not only to invert the unsafe action but to maintain the grammatical structure and operational context required by the STPA method. This constrained generation significantly reduces the likelihood of AI hallucinations and ensures that the generated safety artifacts maintain the necessary rigor to be securely validated by human engineers and seamlessly integrated back into the iStar4Safety visual models.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	16.	}2.6 Related Works\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	17.	}The literature presents several efforts aimed at bridging the gap between requirements and safety analysis. Tools like SafeSecRETS have established the viability of providing computational support for integrated methodologies, allowing engineers to visualize dependencies and map vulnerabilities. Furthermore, various academic proposals have explored the computer-aided modeling of STPA control structures and iStar diagrams independently.\
{\listtext	18.	}However, existing tools generally lack intelligent automation capabilities to derive safety constraints, heavily relying on the user's manual analytical effort for textual and logical derivations across methods. The primary differentiator of RESafety Tool is its integration of Generative AI directly into the methodological workflow. While related works stop at providing a digital canvas or repository for models, RESafety Tool actively participates in the synthesis of Controller Constraints and Safety Requirements, thus acting as an intelligent assistant that significantly lowers the cognitive burden imposed on the safety analyst.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa225\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 \
