\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 {\listtext	21.	}3. RESEARCH METHODOLOGY\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	23.	}3.1 Design Science Research (DSR)\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	24.	}This research is driven by the Design Science Research (DSR) paradigm. In the context of Software Engineering and Information Systems, DSR distinguishes itself from purely observational research by focusing on the creation and evaluation of an innovative, purposeful IT artifact intended to solve an identified organizational or practical problem.\
{\listtext	25.	}By adopting DSR, the primary contribution of this dissertation is not merely an analysis of the theoretical gap between requirements and safety engineering, but the construction of the RESafety Tool tool itself as a concrete solution. The DSR framework ensures a rigorous, iterative cycle of problem understanding, artifact design, practical implementation, and empirical evaluation, ensuring that the developed tool meets both academic rigor and practical utility.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	27.	}3.2 Phases of the Applied Methodology\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	28.	}Following established DSR guidelines, the methodology applied in this work is structured into five sequential and sometimes iterative phases:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Phase 1 - Problem Identification and Motivation:
\f1\b0  Elucidation of the difficulties in executing the RESafety process manually, characterized by high cognitive load and error propensity. This phase was grounded on a literature review of Goal-Oriented Requirements Engineering and Safety Engineering.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Phase 2 - Objectives of a Solution:
\f1\b0  Definition of the specific requirements the proposed tool must fulfill to automate the RESafety process and integrate AI assistance effectively, establishing the functional and non-functional specifications.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Phase 3 - Design and Development:
\f1\b0  The core technical phase, involving the architectural conception and coding of the RESafety Tool tool. This includes the implementation of the Angular frontend, the integration with Quarkus services for authentication and project data, the embedding of the iStar4Safety modeller, and the incorporation of AI APIs via prompt engineering.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Phase 4 - Demonstration:
\f1\b0  Application of the developed artifact (RESafety Tool) to a representative case study of a Safety-Critical System to demonstrate its ability to traverse the seven steps of the RESafety process in a real-world scenario.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Phase 5 - Evaluation:
\f1\b0  Preliminary validation of the tool's utility and usability with domain experts to assess whether the proposed artifact genuinely mitigates the identified problem.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}3.3 Artifact Evaluation Criteria\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The evaluation of the RESafety Tool tool is guided by both technical and user-centric criteria. Technically, the artifact is evaluated on its architectural robustness, ability to maintain bidirectional traceability between iStar4Safety and STPA models, and the consistency of the AI-generated textual outputs (Controller Constraints and Safety Requirements).\
{\listtext	\'95	}From a user-centric perspective, the evaluation utilizes the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM) framework. The assessment instruments focus on two primary constructs:\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Perceived Usefulness (PU):
\f1\b0  The degree to which the analyst believes that using RESafety Tool enhances their performance in conducting integrated safety requirements analysis compared to the manual method.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b Perceived Ease of Use (PEOU):
\f1\b0  The degree to which the analyst believes that using the tool\'97particularly its automated AI workflows and artifact dashboard\'97is free of cognitive and operational effort.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa225\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb225\sa225\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}4. CONCEPTION AND ARCHITECTURE OF THE RESafety Tool\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}4.1 System Overview and Implemented Architecture (Angular Frontend and Quarkus Integration)\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The implemented version of RESafety Tool is centered on an Angular 17 single-page application that organizes the seven RESafety steps into authenticated routes and dedicated workspaces. The frontend uses standalone components, reactive forms, signals, and route guards to separate guest access from the project workspace, thereby guiding the analyst through Home, Scope, iStar4Safety Models, Control Structure, UCAs, Controller Constraints, Loss Scenarios, and Model Update pages.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The frontend integrates with Quarkus through HTTP services exposed under relative \f0\b /api \f1\b0 and \f0\b /auth \f1\b0 paths. In the current codebase, these integrations are concrete for authentication, project listing and creation, project resume retrieval, Step 1 persistence, Step 2 persistence, and AI-assistant endpoints. During local execution, Angular uses a proxy configuration so that browser requests can be routed to Quarkus without additional cross-origin handling.\
{\listtext	\'95	}A distinctive design decision is the reuse of the existing iStar4Safety modeller as an embedded asset loaded inside an iframe. This allows RESafety Tool to combine structured form-based data entry with direct diagram manipulation, rather than forcing all modelling concerns into conventional CRUD screens. In practical terms, Step 2 acts as the bridge between textual project data and the graphical SD/SR representation.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The resulting architecture should therefore be understood as an integrated web environment rather than as a fully evidenced cloud deployment. Step 1 and Step 2 already present persistence and service integration, whereas later stages currently emphasize guided interaction, representative datasets, and traceability views that support demonstration and incremental evolution of the full platform.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}4.2 Application Requirements Specification\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The development of RESafety Tool was guided by a strict set of Functional Requirements (FR) and Non-Functional Requirements (NFR) formulated to address the methodological gap.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Functional Requirements (FR):\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b FR01:
\f1\b0  The system must allow the construction and maintenance of Strategic Dependency (SD) and Strategic Rationale (SR) artifacts through an embedded iStar4Safety modeller combined with structured forms for actors, intentional elements, and dependencies.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b FR02:
\f1\b0  The system must guide authenticated users through the seven iterative steps of the RESafety process via a structured route-based interface and contextual progression rules.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b FR03:
\f1\b0  The system must support project creation, project resumption, and persistence of at least the initial RESafety artifacts, notably Scope (Step 1) and iStar4Safety model information (Step 2), through backend APIs.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b FR04:
\f1\b0  The system must provide AI-assisted artifact generation in the stages where structured prompts and contextual data can reduce analyst effort, especially in scope-definition activities and extensible later-step entry points.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b FR05:
\f1\b0  The system must preserve traceability links among losses, hazards, constraints, responsibilities, UCAs, loss scenarios, and safety requirements through explicit data fields, review tables, and traceability panels.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Non-Functional Requirements (NFR):\
\pard\tx240\tx960\pardeftab720\li960\fi-360\ri0\sl300\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b NFR01 (Architecture):
\f1\b0  The frontend must be developed in Angular using standalone components and reactive interaction patterns, while business data and authentication are consumed from Quarkus-based REST services.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b NFR02 (Persistence):
\f1\b0  Project data and step-specific artifacts must be serializable and recoverable across sessions so analysts can resume partially completed RESafety studies.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b NFR03 (Security and Access Control):
\f1\b0  The application must protect the analysis workspace through token-based authentication, guarded routes, and controlled separation between guest and authenticated navigation flows.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b NFR04 (Interoperability):
\f1\b0  The application must interoperate with backend APIs through stable HTTP contracts, including same-origin relative endpoints in production-style execution and proxy-based integration in local development.\
{\listtext	\'95	}\uc0\u9679 	
\f0\b NFR05 (AI Governance):
\f1\b0  AI-generated outputs must remain reviewable, editable, and rejectable by analysts before becoming part of the persisted project baseline.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sb240\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0
\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}4.3 The AI-Assisted Workflow\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}The implemented AI workflow follows an explicitly human-in-the-loop design. In the frontend, the AI assistant is encapsulated in a dedicated service that exposes generic request methods for generation and question-answer interactions. This service is consumed most substantially in Step 1, where the analyst can invoke AI support for general concerns and safety concerns instead of manually drafting every artifact from scratch.\
{\listtext	\'95	}In the Scope page, the prompts are not free-form. They are programmatically assembled from the current project context, including project resume information, the selected objective text, draft system definition and boundary descriptions, previously generated losses, hazards, constraints, and available Step 2 context when present. The returned answers are then parsed into structured collections such as losses, hazards, safety constraints, responsibilities, and supporting artifacts. Before saving, the frontend merges these suggestions, deduplicates them when possible, labels their origin for the interface, and still allows manual editing or removal.\
{\listtext	\'95	}This design is significant because it turns the AI assistant into a contextual accelerator instead of an autonomous decision-maker. The application does not silently overwrite the analyst's work; it proposes candidate artifacts that remain subject to validation. Such behavior is consistent with the demands of safety-critical engineering, where generated text can be useful for reducing effort but cannot be accepted without domain scrutiny.\
{\listtext	\'95	}The current interface also exposes AI entry points in later steps, such as controller constraints, UCAs, loss scenarios, and iStar4Safety modelling actions. In the present implementation these later entry points represent an extensible interaction pattern, whereas the richest end-to-end AI orchestration is already realized in the scope-definition workflow.\
