\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}4.4 Artifact Dashboard and Traceability\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl300\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}In the implemented application, the notion of an artifact dashboard is distributed across the main workspace rather than concentrated in a single administrative page. The Home page acts as the portfolio dashboard, listing ongoing projects, allowing the creation of new studies, and presenting the full RESafety timeline so that analysts can understand both the current step and the methodological sequence as a whole.\
{\listtext	\'95	}Traceability is made explicit inside the step pages themselves. In Step 1, losses, hazards, constraints, responsibilities, and artifacts are maintained in separate but linked collections, each with validation rules that encode expected dependencies among substeps. In Step 2, these textual definitions are complemented by an embedded modeller and synchronized SD/SR data structures. In Step 6, the interface provides a concrete traceability panel that links a safety requirement to its originating UCA, related hazards, losses, supporting constraints, and control actions. Step 7 extends this perspective with change logs, validation tasks, and integration notes aimed at feeding the results back into the evolving model baseline.\
{\listtext	\'95	}An important characteristic of the current implementation is that traceability is already visible and inspectable even when some later-stage pages are populated with representative datasets for demonstration. This means the artifact relationships are not only described conceptually in the dissertation; they are materially represented in the interface and can guide future consolidation into fully persisted cross-step project data.\
}